(Non-Empirical) In this review, they highlight the high rates of anxiety experience by Palestinians due to their constant exposure to violence. This is found to be mostly caused by the subjugation and violence from Israel.

Transition: Marie et al. (2020) document the severe mental health consequences for Palestinians--predominantly anxiety and PTSD--directly linked to sustained exposure to violence and oppression by Israeli forces. This backdrop of psychological trauma provides a critical context for understanding the broader societal impacts of prolonged conflict as explored by Noah Hefetz (2023). Hefetz introduces the concept of "conflict penalty," emphasizing systematic punitive measures by the Israeli government against Palestinians, further elucidating the layers of conflict-driven adversity faced by the Palestinian population. This shift from individual psychological impacts to systemic punitive strategies offers a broader lens through which to view the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, bridging personal anguish with collective penalty.

