(Empirical) This article goes into the idea of “conflict penalty,” which is the punishing of those perceived as enemies at a higher rate to delegitimize them. This is done primarily done by the Israeli government unto Palestinians.

Transition: From this macroscopic view of governmental strategies by Noah Hefetz (2023), Daniel Bar-Tal (1990) provides a cognitive analysis that illustrates how entrenched misinformation perpetuates these tensions on an individual and group psychological level. Bar-Tal's work highlights the cognitive discrepancies fueled by conflicting narratives, which complicate any attempt at resolving the conflict and achieving constructive discourse. This cognitive dimension adds depth to our understanding of the conflict's resilience and the challenges in bridging ideological divides.

